    summary: 'Hotfix — Cloud Functions only, filed against a live user report: "saat pindahin assignment dengan drag, notif perubahan tetap tidak terkirim padahal sudah deploy" (moving an assignment by drag still sends no change notification, even after deploying). Root-caused directly from production Cloud Functions logs (firebase functions:log), not guesswork: onAssignmentWrite WAS firing correctly and emitting assignment.updated events for every drag/resize/edit (confirmed in logs, "[onAssignmentWrite] event emitted") — the break was one hop downstream. Every single one of those events was then rejected by onEventWrite with "[onEventWrite] INVALID envelope" / errors:["missing actor"], so processEvent() (the actual notification dispatch) never ran — 100% rejection rate, even after the user\'s own most recent functions deploy. Cause: onAssignmentWrite.js#deriveActor() only populates real actor identity for assignment.created/cancelled/completed (read from the assignment record\'s createdBy/cancelledBy/completedBy fields) — assignment.updated/assignment.reassigned (what a plain edit, drag, or resize produces) has no such field to read, so it falls back to {uid:null, role:null, displayName:null}. Realtime Database prunes an object whose every property is null down to nothing on write — so by the time onEventWrite reads the event back via event.data.val(), `actor` has vanished entirely, and events/schema.js#validateEnvelope()\'s `if (!env.actor || typeof env.actor !== \'object\') errors.push(\'missing actor\')` hard-rejected that as invalid. This directly contradicted the envelope\'s own documented contract (`actor, // {uid,role,displayName} (best-effort)`) and how every actual downstream consumer already treats it: dispatcher.js#_isActorRecipient explicitly returns false (never excludes) when actor is absent "Returning false (no actor / ambiguous) means \'send\' — never silently drops a legitimate recipient", and recipients.js/templates.js#actorName both null-guard `event.actor` already. The validator was strictly MORE demanding than the rest of the codebase\'s own established design intent — a genuine contract mismatch, not a deliberate safety check. Consequence: this silently killed notifications for EVERY assignment.updated/assignment.reassigned event since Driver Notification V2 shipped (v1.25.x) — not only drag/resize (js/timeline-interactions.js), but the manual Edit form too, since both write through the identical js/assignments.js#updateAssignmentDirect() → onSaveCallback → saveOneAssignment() → onAssignmentWrite path and produce the same actor shape. assignment.created/cancelled/completed were unaffected (their actor always has at least one non-null field, so RTDB never prunes the whole object away). FIX (functions/src/events/schema.js#validateEnvelope, one line): changed the check from rejecting an ABSENT actor to only rejecting a PRESENT-but-malformed one (`env.actor != null && typeof env.actor !== \'object\'`) — an envelope with no actor at all is now valid, matching the "best-effort" contract and every downstream reader\'s existing null-guard. No change to deriveActor(), the classify()/isMeaningfulChange() threshold logic, the debounce mechanism, or any notification template/recipient logic — this is purely closing a validation gap, not touching business logic. Files modified: functions/src/events/schema.js, js/config.js (this entry). Verified: node --check clean; a targeted reproduction (isolated buildEnvelope/validateEnvelope from the rest of the module, simulating deriveActor()\'s real all-null-actor fallback AND RTDB\'s actual null-pruning behavior on a round-trip) confirmed the exact failure before the fix (`missing actor`, invalid) and the exact resolution after (valid, no errors); scripts/engineering-notification-check.cjs 38/38 passing unchanged (its own positive-path envelope test uses a full, real actor, so behavior there is identical — this fix only changes what happens when actor is absent). Deployed live via `firebase deploy --only functions` — confirmed via firebase functions:log that every function bundling schema.js (onAssignmentWrite, onEventWrite, onRequestWrite, onEngineeringAssignmentWrite, publishEvent, engine.js\'s callers) picked up the new revision (onEventWrite\'s new revision onEventWrite-00013 went ACTIVE at 12:51:01Z). NOT independently verified: an actual end-to-end drag-in-the-real-app-triggers-a-real-push/Telegram-message pass — deploying a synthetic test write against production data to fully exercise recipient resolution and delivery was deliberately avoided to prevent sending an unexpected notification to a real driver; the user was asked to try a real drag and can request a log pull to confirm delivery.',
    highlights: [
      'Root cause found via live Cloud Functions logs (firebase functions:log), not guesswork: onAssignmentWrite emits assignment.updated correctly for every edit/drag, but onEventWrite rejected ALL of them with "missing actor" — 100% silent rejection, confirmed even after the user\'s own prior functions deploy.',
      'Underlying cause: deriveActor() has no writer-identity field to read for a plain update/reassign (only created/cancelled/completed record one), so it falls back to an all-null actor object — and Realtime Database prunes an object whose every property is null down to nothing, so the event reads back with NO actor at all after the round-trip.',
      'The validator\'s hard "missing actor" rejection directly contradicted the envelope\'s own "best-effort" contract and how every real consumer (dispatcher.js, recipients.js, templates.js) already null-guards actor — a genuine contract mismatch, not a deliberate safety gate.',
      'This was never drag-specific: the manual Edit form produces the identical actor shape through the same onSaveCallback → saveOneAssignment() → onAssignmentWrite path, so EVERY assignment.updated/reassigned notification has been silently dropped since Driver Notification V2 (v1.25.x) shipped — drag just happened to be how it was noticed.',
      'One-line fix in events/schema.js#validateEnvelope: reject actor only when present-but-malformed, not merely absent. No change to deriveActor(), classify()/threshold logic, debounce, or any template/recipient code.',
      'Verified with a targeted reproduction that simulates deriveActor()\'s real fallback plus RTDB\'s actual null-pruning behavior (fails pre-fix, passes post-fix); scripts/engineering-notification-check.cjs 38/38 unchanged. Deployed live via firebase deploy --only functions, confirmed ACTIVE on the new revision via functions logs.',
    ],
